### Feature request: ###
jQuery should warn when a selector returns zero matches somehow.    I ask mostly because typically the selector statement is the start of a chain:

This statement ends up being a no-op when an element with id=elementid doesn't exist (for whatever reason, document not ready, server didnt emit it, etc)
```
$("#elementid").on("click", function(e) { console.log("click!"); });
```

Problem is, that no-op is subtle, and difficult to log.  You can test for it first, but this breaks the chain
```
if($("#elementid").length==0) {
  console.log('didnt find #elementid');
} else {
  $("elementid").on("click", function(e) { console.log("click!"); });
}
```

I suppose you could extend jquery, but this particular implementation breaks the chain.
```
jQuery.fn.exists = function () {
    return this.length !== 0;
}
```

Perhaps switching the implementation allows for chaining, but now requires inserting "exists" into all jQuery code:
```
jQuery.fn.exists = function () {
   if(this.length == 0) console.warn("jQuery warning: selector '%s' found zero items.", this.selector);
   return this;
}

$("#elementid").exists().on("click", function(e) { console.log("click!"); });
```

