Under certain circumstances the callbacks in the following code would be called in an unexpected order:

```
window.addEventListener('load', function(e) {
  console.log('native load');
}, true);

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function(e) {
  console.log('native DOMContentLoaded');
}, true);

$(function() {
  console.log("jquery: ready");
});

$(window).on("load", function() {
  console.log("jquery: loaded");
});
```

I would always expect the following output:

```
native DOMContentLoaded
native load
jquery: ready
jquery: loaded
``` 

But it is possible to create a test case where the output is like this (`load` and `ready` are switched).

```
native DOMContentLoaded
native load
jquery: loaded
jquery: ready
``` 

Personally I would say that the order `jquery: loaded` followed by `jquery: ready` should never happen for the given code, but that might be opinion based, therefore, I don't want to insist on this opinion, but I think you should at least adjust the following section in the documentation to point out this behaviour:

[.ready()](https://api.jquery.com/ready/)
> Note that although the DOM always becomes ready before the page is fully loaded, it is usually not safe to attach a load event listener in code executed during a .ready() handler 

