The way a chained promise is resolved in jQuery 3 seems to have changed compared to how it was in jQuery 1.x and 2.x. This does not appear to be related to the async behaviour change, which is well documented.

I have not yet been able to fully pinpoint the problem, but the end result is that jQuery is not consistently resolving a promise with the resolution value. Instead, if the resolution value is itself a promise, it can decide to hide this promise from the caller and instead waits for it directly.

This is undesirable as not all promise chains are a single continuous actions. Having a handler in between the different actions is mandatory and expected.

At Wikimedia, the "OOjs UI" library has an interface for confirmation dialogs. It works like this:

```js
OO.ui.confirm( /* string */ text ).then( function ( /* boolean */ result ) {
 /* .. */
} );
```

The returned promise resolves with a boolean value true/false depending on which button the user pressed.

Internally this method uses a promise to create a dialog, wait for its opening animation, and wait for its closing/cleanup actions.

Source code: <https://github.com/wikimedia/oojs-ui/blob/v0.21.1/src/windows.js#L52-L85>
```js
OO.ui.confirm = function ( text, options ) {
	return OO.ui.getWindowManager().openWindow( 'message', $.extend( {
		message: text
	}, options ) ).then( function ( opened ) {
		return opened.then( function ( closing ) {
			return closing.then( function ( data ) {
				return $.Deferred().resolve( !!( data && data.action === 'accept' ) );
			} );
		} );
	} );
};
```

Most promises return a primitive value or an object with methods that can be called to yield another promise. However in this case, the promise is actually resolved with another promise. The resolution indicates that the opening is done (`opening.then`) and the value given is the promise that will be resolved once the dialog is closed. The latter is malfunctioning in jQuery 3.

It appears it is internally unwrapping this promise layer, thus causing a mismatch between the actual and expected value. Instead of `openWindow().then()` being given the Thenable "opened", it is given the final `data` value (which is not a promise). Thus causing this exception whenever `OO.ui.confirm()` is called:

> **jQuery.Deferred exception: opened.then is not a function**

Downstream bug report: <https://phabricator.wikimedia.org/T163510>

### Link to test case ###

Minimal test case at: <https://codepen.io/Krinkle/pen/JNbNzg?editors=0010>

Compare jQuery 1.11.3, 1.12.4, 2.2.4 and 3.2.1 - with only the latter failing.

