This issue is about listeners with filtering by selector, not just usual listeners. For example:

``` js
$('...').on('click', '.myClass', func);
```

Now jQuery is comparing all selectors each time the event occurs, but this is not optimal and take very long time, especially on mobile phones.

You should use this algorithm:
1. For example, let it be #id selector. Create object: key -> id, value -> handler.
2. When the event occurs do something like that:

   ``` js
   if (elem.handlerById[elem.id]) elem.handlerById[elem.id]();
   ```
3. If you have more than one handler with the same selector filter then merge them into an array.
4. If you need keep order of calling then add counter to every handler and before calling put them all into array and sort by counter.
5. You can optimize many other selector. For example, for [attr=value] selector you need two nested object, first for searching by attr, second for searching by value, or just one object for searching by attr + "=" + value.
6. If you care about file size you can implement it as module and put link at the https://api.jquery.com/on/. When user requires module $.fn.on begins to work fast.
# 

This algorithm works with O(1) speed. Here's example of short implementation that optimize #id selector only, can't work with data, doesn't split handlers by space and doesn't override $.fn.off:

``` js
$.fn.on_original = $.fn.on;

$.fn.on = function(event, selector, handler) {
    if (typeof(selector) !== 'string' || !/^#[a-zA-Z0-9_\-]+$/.test(selector)) {
        return this.on_original(event, selector, handler);
    }

    for (var i = 0; i < this.length; i++) {
        var elem = this[i];

        if (!elem[event]) {
            elem[event] = {
                handlerById: {},
                handlerByClass: {},
                handlerByConcatAttrAndValue: {},
            };
            $(elem).on_original(event, DOMHandler); //Adding common listener without filtering
        }

        elem[event].handlerById[selector.substr(1)] = handler;
    }
};

function DOMHandler(e) {
    var handlerById = this[e.type].handlerById;
    var targetElem = e.target;

    while (targetElem !== this) {
        if (handlerById[targetElem.id]) {
            handlerById[targetElem.id].call(targetElem, e);
        }
        targetElem = targetElem.parentNode;
    }
}
```

