Suppose a number of deferreds are passed to `$.when`, and these deferreds are, or will be, rejected. If a fail callback is added to `$.when`, it should receive the argument which had been passed to the first failed deferred.

That's the behaviour in jQuery 2, and that's how it works in jQuery 3 as well, with one exception: 

```
var dfd1 = $.Deferred(),
    dfd2 = $.Deferred();

// $.when is set up before the deferreds are rejected: 
// works as expected
$.when( dfd1, dfd2 ).fail( function() {
  console.log(arguments);
} );

dfd1.reject( "argument of failed deferred #1" );
dfd2.reject( "argument of failed deferred #2" );

// $.when is set up after the deferreds are rejected: 
// wrong arg passed to callback (in jQuery 3)
$.when( dfd1, dfd2 ).fail( function() {
  console.log(arguments);
} );
```

In jQuery 3, the argument of the _last_ failing deferred is passed to the callback if `$.when` receives the deferreds by the time they are already rejected.

For a working example, including a comparison of jQuery 2 and 3, see http://jsbin.com/wuhesi/4/edit?html,js,console

