The `jQuery.Deferred.exceptionHook` implemented in https://github.com/jquery/jquery/issues/2736 has a problem in that it's called irrespective to whether the error has been handled in a `.catch` handler, or not.

Instead, it should behave as follows:

```
// jQuery.Deferred.exceptionHook should be called
$.Deferred().resolve().then(() => {
  throw new Error('xx');
});

// jQuery.Deferred.exceptionHook should not be called
$.Deferred().resolve().then(() => {
  throw new Error('42');
}).catch(() => {});

// jQuery.Deferred.exceptionHook should be called
$.Deferred().resolve().then(() => {
  throw new Error('42');
}).catch(() => {
  throw new Error('42');
});
```

Instead of fixing `jQuery.Deferred.exceptionHook` behavior, I think it'd be best to implement [`unhandledrejection`](https://github.com/tc39/ecma262/pull/76), which is how e.g. Bluebird currently [does it](http://bluebirdjs.com/docs/api/error-management-configuration.html#global-rejection-events).

