TL;DR, I would love to help reducing jquery's size while keeping the same performance and compatibility

I am the creator of [Umbrella JS](http://umbrellajs.com/), made as a lightweight jquery alternative for modern browsers. I started javascript with jquery many years ago and I'd love to contribute back few things I've learned to try to reduce jquery's size.

While reading jquery's code I've realized that there's many things made in that way in the name of performance; however modern browsers and engines are very different. Take for example the `while()` loop vs `.forEach()` or `.reduce()`, that is traditionally considered a performance improvement:

``` js
var cur = "", i = 0, c;
while ( ( c = arr[ i++ ] ) ) {
  if ( cur.indexOf( " " + c + " " ) < 0 ) {
    cur += c + " ";
  }
}
```

vs

``` js
// This can be generalized and moved out
function joinClassNames(prev, name){
  if (prev.indexOf(" " + name + " ") < 0) {
    prev += name + " ";
  }
  return prev;
};
var cur = arr.reduce(joinClassNames, "");
```

However, now both of these methods are at the same speed (within margin error) as jsperf shows: **[jsperf test](http://jsperf.com/while-vs-foreach-array)**.

