The `end` method terminates the last filter.  I was never fond of it because there is nothing to force a proper pairing with its opening other than indentation.  This is on the developer.

```
$( "ul.first" )
  .find( ".foo" )
    .css( "background-color", "red" )
  .end()
  .find( ".bar" )
    .css( "background-color", "green" );
```

If we deprecate it in favor of `tap` (from Ruby) then inside a function we can query down however deep we need having the full assurance that when we come out of the function, we'll be right back where we started.  The language semantics enforce this and it clearly presents that one wishes to retain the original scope.

```
$( "ul.first" ).tap(function(){
    this.find("foo").css("background-color", "red");
}).find("bar").css("background-color", "green");

//or for consistency...
$( "ul.first" ).tap(function(){
    this.find("foo").css("background-color", "red");
}).tap(function(){
    this.find("bar").css("background-color", "green");
});
```

_The added noise of `function(){}` will go away when ES6 is realized._

```
$( "ul.first" )
  .tap(el => el.find("foo").css("background-color", "red")).
  .tap(el => el.find("bar").css("background-color", "green"));
```

Whether the function called by tap would pass the context in as `this` and\or the first argument offers some room for discussion.  My examples assume it does both.

Where `end` tells us to return to the former scope after the fact (e.g. somewhere after the original `find`), `tap` tells us up front that we're going to want to maintain the scope.  To my way of thinking stating that earlier is better than later.

It also provides an opportunity for the use of higher-order functions which means a greater potential for reuse.  The `end` method offers no such opportunity.

```
function bg(selector, color){
    return function(){
        this.find(selector).css("background-color", color);
    }
}

$("ul.first").
    tap(bg("foo", "red")).
    tap(bg("bar", "green"));
```

Or alternately, provide another version of `find`, `filter`, etc. (though I prefer `tap`):

```
$( "ul.first" ).find("foo", function(){
    this.css("background-color", "red");
}).find("bar").css("background-color", "green");
```

The added benefit of `tap` is that we can easily see what's being returned from a function:

```
function spreadChristmasCheer(el){
    return el.
        tap(bg("foo", "red")).
        tap(bg("bar", "green"));      
}
```

So now we can reuse such a function in a number of ways:

```
spreadChristmasCheer(el);
el.tap(spreadChristmasCheer);
el.find(".christmas-tree").tap(spreadChristmasCheer).find(".presents").remove();
```

