Suppose we have the Deferred object and try to set handlers on progress for both `.promise()` and `.then()` objects:

``` js
var d = $.Deferred().notify();
d.promise().progress(function(){ console.log('promise') });
d.then().progress(function(){ console.log('then') });
```

This works as expected, both progress handlers will fire. But if we try to set progress handlers for resolved Deferred, the result will be different:

``` js
var d = $.Deferred().notify().resolve(); // Look there, I'm resolved.
d.promise().progress(function(){ console.log('promise') });
d.then().progress(function(){ console.log('then') });
```

Only first handler will fire. The problem in [tuples order](https://github.com/jquery/jquery/blob/ab20d9d24f0a95df382c02e9ef3dcc4adb86e4f1/src/deferred.js#L12-L14). `Progress` tuple come last, and therefor, when [newDefer.notify()](https://github.com/jquery/jquery/blob/ab20d9d24f0a95df382c02e9ef3dcc4adb86e4f1/src/deferred.js#L39) is called, newDefer is already resolved and doesn't accept notifying.

This bug is similar to https://github.com/jquery/jquery/issues/1894, but slightly different.

http://jsfiddle.net/sp6a117y/

Analogous to #1894 in both [cause](https://github.com/jquery/jquery/blob/74ae5444832b2fb966768a97281d2ad8c088bc58/src/deferred.js#L33-L37) and solution. The new promise never sees progress at all because `.done` is called on it before `.progress`:

``` js
jQuery.Deferred().resolve().pipe(function() {
    var dfd = jQuery.Deferred().notify( "a" );
    dfd.notify( "b" ).resolve( 1 );
    return dfd;
})
.progress( expectsInvocationWithB );
```

